The Familiar in the New Antisemitism
Why do so many Holocaust survivors sense emerging threats to Judaism before they become generally visible?
Because they know that the supposedly "harmless" hints can turn into accusations and ultimately lead to discrimination that is then legally codified.
At this point, hysteria sets in.
The survivors raise the alarm because they know what's at stake.
Thus, they strengthen our democracies in a way that only they can.
We listen to the survivors so that we too may survive.
Since the first round of the French presidential elections, it has become clear that we have every reason to listen.
But not only demagogues like Jean Marie Le Pen or other crude right-wing extremists in Europe cause problems.
In the 20th century, people who saw themselves as "intellectuals" often became mere opportunists for fascism or communism, without joining a party with the corresponding ideological background.
In the 21st century, we are dealing with people - the "educated bourgeoisie" in conjunction with mass media, politics, government, and universities - who condemn Israel in a language that often resembles that of the opportunists of these antidemocratic movements.
This is not the majority opinion in the Western world—thankfully, not yet—but these are the voices of a powerful and influential minority.
At this point, mention should be made of the example of the French ambassador to the United Kingdom: Recently, during a dinner party in London, he referred to Israel as "this damned little country."
His vulgar manner of speaking is not particularly alarming.
What is rather alarming, however, are the reactions to it.
He was neither recalled by his government nor did the government demand Blair's recall. In public, the matter was dismissed as just another scandal.
The French press portrayed the ambassador in all seriousness as a victim of British small-time informants and not as a result of his own contemptible attitude.
Unfortunately, the French ambassador to the United Kingdom has many allies among Europe's elites.
Ambassador Bernard, however, did us a favor: Through him, it became clear how widespread these new anti-Jewish resentments are.
As one columnist so aptly put it: Israel has become a hate object, the very mention of which one dares not to utter.
But we are not only allowed to say it—we are even obligated to speak it out.
In view of the daily attacks against Jews and synagogues in France, we must not remain silent.
It is a disgrace for all of Europe that so many French Jews cannot send their children to school without having to worry about their safety.
Anti-Semitic attacks are also being reported elsewhere. In Berlin and London, in Switzerland, Italy, Sweden, the Netherlands, and parts of Eastern Europe.
We must not remain silent about the fact that denial of the Holocaust is becoming commonplace. Likewise, we must not remain silent about the comparisons that antisemites and anti-Zionists draw between Israel and the Third Reich.
While in a Palestinian television broadcast Israeli soldiers are portrayed as rapists and cold-blooded murderers, a Syrian newspaper wrote that we must "stand up to the new Nazi plague emerging in Israel."
The Mufti of Jerusalem said: "It is not my fault that Hitler hated the Jews. They are almost hated everywhere."
During the television broadcast of a Friday prayer on Palestinian television, the preacher urged Muslims to "show no mercy to the Jews. No matter where you are, kill them and these Americans who are just like them."
What we should think about in connection with antisemitism is that it always begins with the Jews, but never ends with the Jews.
If antisemitism is not kept in check, it almost always leads to attacks on other groups and minorities and ultimately undermines democratic institutions and the rule of law.
The fight against antisemitism is therefore the task of Jews as well as non-Jews.
Currently, the points of attack in this conflict are more blurred than ever before, because a remarkable aspect of today's antisemitism is its flexibility.
Although the goal of antisemitism always remains the same - namely, to attack Jews - it nevertheless changes its face, its strategy, its justifications, and even its vocabulary.
Once, the Jewish religion was the target.
When they did not surrender, the Jews were expelled or killed.
When in the 19th century the theory of race captivated people, Jews were attacked because of their belonging to a wicked race.
With the existence of the State of Israel as a source of pride and security for most Jews, Zionism is now denigrated as a racist ideology.
I do not equate criticism of Israel with antisemitism.
Just as with other nations, it is entirely legitimate to critically oppose certain political strategies and decisions of Israel.
However, Antizionism is becoming increasingly similar to antisemitism.
Anti-Zionists sometimes claim that they are not against the Jews, but "only" against the Jewish state.
Imagine someone saying: "I'm only against the existence of the United Kingdom, but I'm not anti-British!"
Or if someone claimed: "I love the Swedish people, but Sweden should be abolished."
They wouldn't believe them.
It is difficult to love or respect a people, but to hate their state.
And yet, in the context of Israel, there are people who claim to be exactly able to do that.
In various UN organizations, insults against Israel are on the agenda.
This demonization of the only democratic state in the Middle East is a central point of this new antisemitism.
When Israel is described as "the enemy of all that is good and the source of all that is evil," the "teaching of contempt" circulates within the UN, as Professor Irwin Cotler, a member of the Canadian Parliament, expresses it.
This permanent portrayal of a nation as the enemy of humanity is, in reality, a campaign against the Jewish people.
Thus, the numerous anti-Jewish attacks in many countries are based on the demonization of Israel, which makes use of antisemitic terminology.
Attacks on synagogues are often triggered by the use of this defamatory language in connection with the Middle East.
Compared to previous anti-Jewish outbreaks, today's antisemitism is less about attacks on individual Jews and more about an attack against the "collective Jew," that is, against the state of Israel.
Such attacks, however, have triggered a chain reaction of assaults on individual Jews and Jewish institutions throughout Europe and Latin America.
Earlier, the most dangerous antisemites were those who wanted to make the world free of Jews.
The most dangerous antisemites today are those who want to make the world free of a Jewish state.
